This allowed us to control the Pi from the laptop.

7. ROS 2 Installation

We moved from ROS1 concepts to ROS 2 Jazzy.

Installed

ROS 2 Jazzy

Colcon build tools

RViz2

Navigation-related dependencies

Workspace creation
mkdir -p ~/ros2_ws/src
cd ~/ros2_ws
colcon build

Then we sourced:

source /opt/ros/jazzy/setup.bash
source ~/ros2_ws/install/setup.bash
8. YDLIDAR Driver Setup
Clone driver
cd ~/ros2_ws/src
git clone https://github.com/YDLIDAR/ydlidar_ros2_driver.git
Build
cd ~/ros2_ws
colcon build --symlink-install
Configure X2

We edited the parameter file:

X2.yaml

Baudrate = 115200

Port = /dev/ttyUSB0

9. Verify LiDAR Data

We launched the driver:

ros2 launch ydlidar_ros2_driver ydlidar_launch.py

Then checked topics:

ros2 topic list

Important topic:

/scan

We verified scan frequency:

ros2 topic hz /scan

Result was approximately 11–12 Hz, confirming the LiDAR was working properly.

10. SLAM Toolbox Installation

We used slam_toolbox for real-time mapping.

Launch
ros2 launch slam_toolbox online_async_launch.py

This created:

/map

/map_metadata

/tf

/pose

11. TF (Transform) Configuration

Initially SLAM failed because the laser frame was not connected.

We discovered:

LiDAR frame = laser_frame

Robot base frame = base_link

Static transform
ros2 run tf2_ros static_transform_publisher 0 0 0.02 0 0 0 base_link laser_frame

This was a critical step that connected the LiDAR to the robot coordinate system.

12. RViz Visualization

We opened RViz2 and configured:

Fixed Frame: laser_frame

Added LaserScan → Topic /scan

Added Map → Topic /map

Added TF display

At first only scan points appeared; after the TF fix, walls and the occupancy grid map became visible.

13. Localization & Mapping

With SLAM running, the system simultaneously:

Mapping (SLAM)

Converted LiDAR scans into an occupancy grid

Built a 2D floor plan of the surroundings

Localization

Estimated the LiDAR/robot position on the map

Published pose information on /pose

This achieved Simultaneous Localization and Mapping.

14. Motor Control Programming

We wrote a Python ROS2-compatible motor controller using lgpio.

Logic implemented

Forward: all motors run

Obstacle detected: stop immediately

Turn Left: left-side control logic

Turn Right: right-side control logic

15. Ultrasonic Obstacle Avoidance

We integrated the HC-SR04 sensor.

Working logic

Measure distance continuously

If distance < threshold (e.g., 20 cm) → STOP

Then choose a new direction

This provided a secondary safety layer in addition to LiDAR.

